+Wikipedia-Note-Taking Software
+Wikipedia-Mindmapping

Qualities:
* Local - accessible offline also
* Sync - maintain synchronized copies across multiple devices
* Search - find what you are looking for
* Web Clipper - clip quickly from browser (main search tool)
* ScanTailor - import scans and photographed documents etc.
* Collaboration/Whiteboarding - realtime collaboration with other users
* Export/Intercompatability - data to plain text, s-expr, XML, Orgmode, Markdown, PDF, ODF/ODT, SQL
* Native - wait for pil21; until then, create web version
* Security/Encryption - tricky...do string/num encryption for now?

Other mentions:
* fuzzy search/auto completion - with tags -> speeds it up by show list, select
* revision control
* linking notes
* ink-pen input
* insert objects - only onenote can insert anything
* organization capabilities - folders, notebooks, tags, hierarchial/flat
  Methods:
    * GTD
    * Zettelkasten
* drawn annotations
* code annotations
* highlighting

Business Plan:
1. Target power users on desktop
   1. Test with Linux users
   2. Develop web version for Win/MacOS users (and mobile)
2. Integrate editing functionality for sounds, images, vide etc.
3. Target mobile users
4. Sell Raspberry Pi devices that run it as userspace
5. Develop full-blown OS

* Pay for sync/backup and collab (require P2P or a server)
* Poss server processing abilities (for mobile and/or power users)
  * Cheaper to up/dl vs cpu power
* Encryption
* Private notes
  * Like GitHub
* Autodefrag - should make feature

* 3 pricing tiers
* Free for edu

Goal:
* Evolve the power of orgmode/emacs to all data

